  <!-- ===== OUR APPROACH ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section" id="approach">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The SHARP Method</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">Why the SHARP Method produces O-Level English results other approaches can&rsquo;t</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Developed by Jeremy Lim (LLB Hons, NUS Faculty of Law), the SHARP Method adapts legal analytical precision to O-Level English exam technique.</p>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">See</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Most students lose marks before they write a single word &mdash; because they misread what the question is actually asking. In the See step, your child learns to decode every O-Level question the way a lawyer reads a contract: what is the command word? What text type does the examiner expect? What are the hidden constraints buried in the rubric? For comprehension, this means identifying whether a question is literal (answer is in the text), inferential (answer must be deduced), or evaluative (answer requires judgement). For composition, it means spotting whether the prompt calls for narrative, expository, or argumentative writing &mdash; and what register, audience, and purpose are implied. By the time your child puts pen to paper, they already know exactly what success looks like.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Hit</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Once the question type is clear, your child selects the precise framework built for that question. This isn&rsquo;t generic advice &mdash; it&rsquo;s a specific, named tool for each paper section: STAMP CARD for editing (a 9-category error sweep), RAWCP for situational writing (Register, Audience, Writing format, Content points, Purpose), CAPS for narrative composition (Characters, Arc, Plot, Setting), P-E-E-L for expository and argumentative writing (Point, Evidence, Explanation, Link), Core Move for inference questions (quote the text, state the inference, explain the connection), and ACED for visual text comprehension (Audience, Content, Effect, Design). Each framework maps directly to the Cambridge mark scheme &mdash; so every mark your child earns is deliberate, not accidental.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Apply</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">This is where frameworks become actual writing. Your child applies the chosen tool to a real past-paper question under guided conditions &mdash; not passively watching a model answer, but actively constructing their own response with live tutor intervention. For composition, this means building a full essay outline using CAPS or P-E-E-L before writing the first sentence, so the argument has structure before it has words. For comprehension, it means writing P-E-E-L answers where every sentence earns a mark. Jeremy provides real-time feedback on screen-shared documents &mdash; flagging weak topic sentences, vague evidence, and missing content points as they happen, not a week later when the moment has passed. The small class size (max 6) means every student gets at least three individual feedback touches per session.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Refine &amp; Practise</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">The steps that turn B-grade students into A-grade students. Your child self-checks every response against a paper-specific checklist: Did the situational writing match the correct register? Does the comprehension answer include a text reference? Is the summary under 80 words without dropping content points? Are verb tenses consistent throughout the narrative? Then comes retrieval practice &mdash; the most underrated study technique in education. Your child rewrites key answers from memory, reinforcing the framework until the process becomes automatic. This is how exam technique transfers from the classroom to the exam hall: not through last-minute revision, but through spaced, deliberate repetition that locks each framework into long-term memory.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">STAMP CARD &mdash; Editing</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Subject-verb agreement, Tense, Articles, Modifiers, Prepositions, Conjunctions, Apostrophes, Run-ons, Determiners &mdash; nine categories, memorised in order, applied as a systematic sweep through every editing passage. Most students approach the editing section by reading the passage and hoping errors jump out. They don&rsquo;t. STAMP CARD replaces hope with method: your child reads the passage nine times, each time checking for one specific error category. The first pass catches subject-verb disagreements. The second catches tense shifts. The third catches missing or wrong articles. By the ninth pass, every error type has been systematically hunted. The 10 marks in Paper 1A are the easiest marks on the entire paper &mdash; if your child has a system.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">ACED &mdash; Paper 2 Visual Text</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Audience, Content, Effect, Design &mdash; four dimensions that unlock every visual text question the examiner can set. When your child sees a poster, flyer, or advertisement in Paper 2, ACED tells them exactly what to look for: Who is the target audience, and how do you know? What claims does the text make, and what evidence supports them? What persuasive effect do the design choices create &mdash; colour, font size, imagery, layout? And what is the overall purpose the text achieves? Most students write vague responses like &lsquo;the poster is colourful and eye-catching.&rsquo; ACED produces precise ones that link specific design elements to specific persuasive effects. Each dimension maps to a mark in the Cambridge rubric.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== QUESTION-TYPE FRAMEWORKS ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section" id="frameworks">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Question-Type Frameworks</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">A named framework for every question type on the O-Level paper</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Most tuition centres teach &ldquo;how to write better.&rdquo; We teach your child exactly which tool to reach for &mdash; and exactly how to use it &mdash; for every section of every paper.</p>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Editing &mdash; STAMP CARD</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 1A tests 10 specific grammar and vocabulary errors. STAMP CARD gives your child a 9-category mnemonic sweep &mdash; Subject-verb agreement, Tense, Articles, Modifiers, Prepositions, Conjunctions, Apostrophes, Run-ons, Determiners &mdash; applied in sequence on every editing passage. Instead of reading the passage once and hoping errors reveal themselves, your child reads it nine times with one focused lens each pass. The method catches silent errors that native speakers routinely miss: the singular subject paired with a plural verb three clauses away, the tense shift buried mid-paragraph, the missing article before an uncountable noun. Cambridge awards 10 marks here. Our students treat them as free marks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Situational Writing &mdash; RAWCP + P-A-R</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 1B asks students to write in a specific format for a specific audience &mdash; but most students jump straight to content and forget about register, format, and tone. RAWCP (Register, Audience, Writing format, Content points, Purpose) is a pre-writing checklist your child runs before the first sentence. P-A-R (Purpose, Audience, Register) then guides every word choice: is this a formal letter to a principal, or an informal email to a friend? Should the tone be persuasive, informative, or advisory? Your child learns to match vocabulary, sentence structure, and closing conventions to the exact text type the examiner has specified &mdash; whether it&rsquo;s a formal proposal, an informal email, a report, or a speech. The 30 marks here reward precision of format as much as quality of content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Narrative Composition &mdash; CAPS</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 1C narrative prompts require a story with structure &mdash; not a rambling sequence of events. CAPS (Characters, Arc, Plot, Setting) gives your child a four-point planning framework they complete in five minutes before writing. Characters: who is the protagonist, and what do they want? Arc: what tension or conflict drives the story? Plot: what are the three key events (setup, complication, resolution)? Setting: where and when does the story take place, and how does the setting shape the mood? The result is a composition that reads like a story examiners want to keep reading &mdash; with a clear turning point, sensory detail, and a resolution that doesn&rsquo;t feel rushed.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Expository &amp; Argumentative &mdash; P-E-E-L</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">For Paper 1C expository and argumentative prompts, P-E-E-L (Point, Evidence, Explanation, Link) structures every body paragraph into a unit that earns full marks. Point: a clear topic sentence that directly addresses the question. Evidence: a specific example, statistic, or real-world reference &mdash; not a vague generalisation. Explanation: two to three sentences that explain how the evidence supports the point, showing the examiner your child can reason, not just assert. Link: a sentence that connects back to the thesis and transitions to the next paragraph. Most students can make a point and give an example. The marks are in the explanation &mdash; the analytical layer where your child demonstrates why the evidence matters.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Comprehension &mdash; Core Move</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 2 inference questions are where most students lose the most marks &mdash; because inference feels subjective. Core Move makes it systematic: quote a specific phrase from the text, state what the phrase implies (not what it literally says), and explain the reasoning that connects the quote to the inference. For example, if the text says &lsquo;she pressed her lips together and turned to the window,&rsquo; your child learns to quote the phrase, infer that the character is suppressing emotion or disagreement, and explain that the physical action signals internal conflict the character chooses not to voice. The method forces students to anchor every inference in textual evidence &mdash; which is exactly what Cambridge mark schemes require.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Visual Text &mdash; ACED</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 2 visual text questions test whether your child can analyse an advertisement, poster, or flyer. ACED (Audience, Content, Effect, Design) provides the four lenses examiners use to mark responses. Audience: who is the text targeting, and what language or imagery signals this? Content: what specific claims or information does the text present? Effect: what emotional or persuasive response does the text aim to create? Design: how do layout choices (font, colour, image placement, whitespace) contribute to the text&rsquo;s purpose? Each lens produces one mark-worthy observation. Your child learns to write responses that link specific design elements to specific persuasive effects, rather than vague statements about colours being &lsquo;eye-catching.&rsquo;</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Summary &mdash; 80-Word Compression</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 2 summary questions ask your child to compress a passage into exactly 80 words while retaining every content point the examiner credits. Our method is three steps: first, number every content point in the passage (typically 8&ndash;10 points across 2&ndash;3 paragraphs). Second, paraphrase each point using your own words &mdash; not synonym-swapping, but genuine restructuring. Third, combine points into compound sentences to stay within the word limit without dropping marks. Cambridge examiners penalise lifting (using the author&rsquo;s exact words) and reward concision. We drill one timed summary per session &mdash; students track their word count, content point hit rate, and paraphrase quality over the term.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Oral Communication &mdash; 1-2-1 Structure</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 4 oral communication tests your child&rsquo;s ability to discuss a visual stimulus with an examiner. 1-2-1 gives a clear response architecture: state one clear opinion in the opening sentence, support it with two specific reasons (each backed by a personal example or real-world reference), then restate the stance in the closing sentence. The structure prevents the two most common oral mistakes: rambling without a clear position, and giving one-word answers that die in silence. We practise through recorded mock orals where students watch their own playback &mdash; checking pace, filler words, and eye contact. The difference between a pass and a distinction in oral is not vocabulary; it&rsquo;s structure and confidence.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SHARP PLAYBOOK ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section playbook-section" id="playbook">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The SHARP Playbook</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">SHARP, mapped to every section of the O-Level paper</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">Each row is a paper section. Each column is one SHARP step. Read across to see exactly what your child does at every stage &mdash; from decoding the question to retrieval practice.</p>

      <div class="playbook-matrix" role="table" aria-label="SHARP method mapped to each O-Level English paper section">
        <div class="playbook-matrix__head" role="row">
          <div class="playbook-matrix__col-label" role="columnheader">Paper section</div>
          {sharpSteps.map((step) => (
            <div class="playbook-matrix__step" role="columnheader">
              <span class="playbook-letter" aria-hidden="true">{step.letter}</span>
              <span class="playbook-step-name">{step.name}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        {playbookRows.map((row, i) => (
          <div class="playbook-matrix__row" role="row">
            <div class="playbook-matrix__row-label" role="rowheader">
              <span class="playbook-paper">{row.paper}</span>
              <span class="playbook-section-name">{row.section}</span>
            </div>
            {row.steps.map((cell, j) => (
              <div class="playbook-matrix__cell" role="cell" data-step={sharpSteps[j].letter} data-step-name={sharpSteps[j].name}>
                <div class="playbook-matrix__cell-body">
                  <strong>{cell.title}</strong>
                  <span>{cell.note}</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="playbook-cta">
