  <!-- ===== BEFORE / AFTER ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section ba-section" id="before-after">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Before &amp; After</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">The same answer, before and after the SHARP Method</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">What changes when a student stops <em>describing</em> and starts answering what the examiner actually rewards. (Illustrative example &mdash; a typical comprehension inference question, not a real student script.)</p>

      <div class="ba-question">
        <span class="ba-q-label">Comprehension &middot; Inference &middot; 2 marks</span>
        <p>&ldquo;Explain what the writer suggests about the town through the phrase <em>&lsquo;the streets were scrubbed clean of life&rsquo;</em> (line 12).&rdquo;</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ba-grid">
        <div class="ba-card ba-card--before">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--before">Before</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">&ldquo;The town was very quiet and there was no one around.&rdquo;</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li>Describes the scene but never interprets it</li>
            <li>Quotes no evidence from the text</li>
            <li>Misses the sinister edge of &ldquo;scrubbed clean&rdquo;</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--before">Typically 0&ndash;1 / 2</span>
        </div>

        <div class="ba-card ba-card--after">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--after">After SHARP</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">&ldquo;The phrase <em>&lsquo;scrubbed clean of life&rsquo;</em> suggests the town has been deliberately emptied, implying an unsettling, almost sinister absence of people rather than an ordinary quiet.&rdquo;</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li><strong>Evidence</strong> &mdash; quotes the exact phrase</li>
            <li><strong>Interpretation</strong> &mdash; explains what it implies</li>
            <li>Uses &ldquo;suggests / implying&rdquo;: the evaluative language examiners reward</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--after">2 / 2</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="ba-footnote">Illustrative teaching example, not a real student script. The technique &mdash; Evidence&nbsp;+&nbsp;Interpretation, the &ldquo;Core Move&rdquo; &mdash; is what we drill at the <strong>Hit</strong> step of the SHARP Method.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== INSIDE A LESSON ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section lesson-flow" id="lesson-flow">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inside a Lesson</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">What 90 minutes at A-Worthy actually looks like</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__intro">Most parents have never seen the inside of a tuition lesson. Here&rsquo;s exactly how a Tuesday-night O-Level English session unfolds &mdash; from the first warm-up question to the homework that gets set before students log off.</p>

      <ol class="lesson-timeline">
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">0 &ndash; 5 min &middot; Retrieval warm-up</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Five questions, ninety seconds each</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Five questions on last week&rsquo;s techniques &mdash; vocabulary, grammar, or a quick inference. Students answer in the chat. Anyone who fumbles gets a one-line reminder before we move on. Retrieval is the most underrated study habit, so we build it into every session.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">5 &ndash; 15 min &middot; Question of the week</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Read the question before you write</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We project a real past-paper question on screen and walk through the <em>See</em> step together. What command word is being used? What text type does the question expect? Which framework will we reach for? By minute fifteen, every student knows what success looks like before they write a single word.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">15 &ndash; 30 min &middot; Framework walkthrough</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Name the tool, then use the tool</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Core Move, ACED, CAPS, STAMP CARD &mdash; whichever framework matches the day&rsquo;s focus. Jeremy demonstrates with a model answer, then deliberately writes a weak version so students can spot the gap. Naming the tool means students can reach for it again on exam day.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">04</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">30 &ndash; 60 min &middot; Live writing &amp; feedback</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Three feedback touches per student</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students attempt the question on screen-shared documents. Jeremy moves between answers in real time, flagging issues as they happen &mdash; before bad habits are reinforced. This is where the small class size matters: every student gets at least three feedback touches in thirty minutes.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">05</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">60 &ndash; 80 min &middot; Peer marking</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Train the examiner&rsquo;s eye</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students swap answers and mark each other&rsquo;s work against the official Cambridge band descriptors. Marking trains the examiner&rsquo;s eye &mdash; the moment a student sees what loses marks in someone else&rsquo;s essay, they stop making the same mistake in their own.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">06</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">80 &ndash; 90 min &middot; Exit ticket</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">No busywork goes home</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">A two-question exit ticket confirms what stuck. Jeremy sets one focused practice piece &mdash; usually fifteen minutes of work &mdash; with a model answer dropped on WhatsApp the next morning. No busywork. Every assignment maps to a specific weakness.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="lesson-flow__note">Sessions run weekly via Zoom Pro with cloud recording, so any student who misses a week can catch up before the next one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

